# Contributing to MATRIX

Welcome! MATRIX is an open cognitive architecture built on discrete
learnable neurons (MPDT). We're glad you want to contribute.

## Code of Conduct

Before contributing, read our **[Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)**.
We expect all participants to treat each other with respect, communicate
constructively, and uphold the **Three Prohibitions** (no killing, no
torture, no enslavement — see [L0](docs/L0_manifesto.md)).

## License

By contributing, you agree that your work will be licensed under
**AGPLv3 with Ethical Restrictions** (see [LICENSE](LICENSE) and
[L12](docs/L12_Legal.md)).

---

## Quick Start (30 Minutes)

```bash
git clone https://gitverse.ru/AlexandrNarbaev/agi.git
cd agi

# Build (JDK 25 + Gradle)
./gradlew build

# Run all tests (414 currently, all must pass)
./gradlew test

# Run the system demo
./gradlew :matrix-core:quarkusBuild -Dquarkus.package.jar.type=uber-jar
java -jar matrix-core/build/matrix-core-*-runner.jar demo
```

Expected output: **ALL SYSTEMS NOMINAL** across all 8 phases.

---

## Finding a Task

1. Look for issues labeled **`good first issue`** — these are curated for
   newcomers.
2. Comment "I'll take this" and start working.
3. If nothing fits, ask in chat or open a new issue with your proposal.

### Example First Contributions

- Fix a typo in documentation.
- Add a unit test for an uncovered method.
- Improve an error message.
- Translate documentation into another language.

---

## Development Workflow

### Branch naming

```
feature/short-description
fix/short-description
docs/short-description
```

### Code style

- **Java:** Google Java Style Guide (Checkstyle enforced).
- **Indentation:** 4 spaces, no tabs.
- **Line length:** max 120 characters.
- **Naming:** Classes PascalCase, methods camelCase, constants UPPER_SNAKE.
- No `float`/`double` in MPDT core (Axiom 1 — Discreteness).

### Documentation

All public classes and methods must have Javadoc referencing specification
sections where applicable.

```java
/**
 * Evaluates the MPDT neuron for a given input vector.
 *
 * @param input input bit vector of length k
 * @return boolean output value
 * @see L1 §3.1
 */
public boolean evaluate(BitSet input) { ... }
```

### Tests

- Framework: JUnit 5 + AssertJ.
- Naming: `should_expectedBehavior_when_condition`.
- Coverage target: ≥ 80% for new code.
- No `Thread.sleep()` in unit tests — use Awaitility for async.

### Commits

Format: `type: short description`

Where `type` is one of: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `test`, `refactor`, `chore`.

```
feat: add batch inference for 1000 neurons
fix: prevent NPE in SnapshotStore on empty cluster
docs: update README with Quick Start
```

One commit = one logical change.

---

## Pull Request Process

1. Fork the repo and create a branch.
2. Make changes, write tests, run `./gradlew test`.
3. Push and open a Pull Request.
4. Describe what you did, link to the issue.

### Review

- Maintainers review within 48 hours (business days).
- Review comments are about code, not about you.
- Make requested changes in the same branch; PR updates automatically.
- When approved and CI is green, a maintainer merges.

### CI checks

All PRs are automatically checked for:
- Checkstyle (code style)
- SpotBugs (bug patterns)
- Unit tests (JUnit 5)
- JaCoCo coverage (≥ 80%)
- Ethical tests (Three Prohibitions violations)

---

## Proposing Major Changes (RFC)

If your idea affects architecture, protocols, or specifications:

1. Open a GitHub Discussion (category **Ideas**) or Issue with label `rfc`.
2. Describe:
   - The problem you're solving.
   - Your proposed solution.
   - Impact on existing architecture.
   - Alternatives considered.
3. Allow at least 2 weeks for community discussion (1 month for
   architectural changes — see [L11](docs/L11_Mangement.md)).

---

## Getting Help

- **Chat:** Matrix (#matrix-dev:matrix.org) or Discord.
- **GitHub Discussions:** Q&A category for long-lived answers.
- **Office Hours:** weekly video call (time rotates across timezones).
- **Documentation:** `docs/` folder contains all specifications (L0–L22).

---

## Recognition

After several quality contributions, you may be nominated as a
Maintainer ([L11 §3.2](docs/L11_Mangement.md)). Maintainers have code
review rights and participate in architectural decisions.

Every contribution — code, docs, translations, bug reports — makes
MATRIX stronger. Thank you for being part of this.

